## Finding: Stakeholder Sign-Off and Operational Readiness Gate Missing

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Phase 6 (Handoff) contains api_reference, community_management, disaster_recovery, doc_reorganize, feature_walkthrough, and user_documentation. None of these skills address the formal handoff gate: getting sign-off from stakeholders (product owners, customers, operations teams) that the product is ready for general availability. "Handoff" as a phase implies transferring ownership from the build team to an operations/support/user base — yet there is no skill governing the readiness review checklist, acceptance criteria verification, stakeholder approval workflow, or the formal declaration that handoff is complete. Without this, the phase has no authoritative ending condition.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "operational_readiness_review", Phase 6, triggers: "Run pre-GA readiness check", "Stakeholder sign-off checklist", "Operational readiness review for [project]". Scope: Defines the formal readiness gate that gates transition from build/beta to GA, covering acceptance criteria verification against Phase 3-5 outputs, stakeholder sign-off matrix (who must approve what), operational readiness scorecard, and the formal handoff declaration document.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without a readiness gate, Phase 7 (Maintenance) can begin on a product that has not been formally accepted. Phase 5.75 (Beta) feedback may not be formally resolved before handoff occurs. Upstream phases have no guarantee their deliverables were verified at handoff.

---

## Finding: Support Team Enablement Has No Dedicated Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: user_documentation covers end-user help centers and in-app contextual help. feature_walkthrough covers developer-oriented walkthroughs. disaster_recovery covers incident response runbooks. None of these address the specific work of enabling a support team: training support agents on the product, creating internal support playbooks distinct from public docs, giving support staff tools to diagnose common issues, and documenting escalation paths. Support team enablement is a distinct handoff deliverable — the people who answer user questions need different materials than users or engineers.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "support_enablement", Phase 6, triggers: "Enable support team for [product]", "Create support playbook for [feature]", "Internal support documentation". Scope: Creates the internal knowledge base and training materials specifically for support agents, including diagnostic decision trees, escalation matrices, known issue trackers with workarounds, and a support agent onboarding checklist distinct from end-user documentation.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 (Maintenance) depends on a functioning support layer. Without support enablement, incoming maintenance issues will be routed incorrectly, response times will be slow, and engineering will be interrupted with issues that support should handle.

---

## Finding: SLA Definition and Handoff of SLA Commitments Is Absent

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: disaster_recovery defines incident severity levels (SEV1-SEV4) and recovery time targets per scenario. However, no skill addresses the formal definition of Service Level Agreements (SLAs) at handoff: what uptime is promised, what response times are committed, what the penalty or remediation policy is, and how these are communicated to customers. The disaster_recovery runbooks are operational tools — SLA handoff is a contractual and communication act that must happen at the boundary of Phase 6. Without formalized SLAs, the downstream support and maintenance team operates without targets.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "sla_handoff", Phase 6, triggers: "Define SLA for [service]", "Create SLA documentation for handoff", "SLA commitments for [product]". Scope: Documents the formal SLA commitments being transferred at handoff — uptime targets, response time SLOs, error budget definitions, escalation SLAs, and the communication artifact that conveys these to customers and the operations team inheriting the product.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 (Maintenance) cannot measure its own success without defined SLAs. DORA metrics (change failure rate, MTTR) have no context without SLO baselines. Phase 5 and 5.75 (Ship/Beta) established monitoring — but the targets for that monitoring are only defined at this handoff.

