## Finding: Monitoring and Alerting Handoff Is Not Addressed

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: disaster_recovery includes a maintenance schedule and status page bookmarks. However, it assumes the monitoring infrastructure already exists and the team knows what to watch. No Phase 6 skill covers the explicit handoff of monitoring ownership: transferring alerting configurations, defining who owns which alert, setting up on-call rotations with tooling (PagerDuty, OpsGenie), or documenting what each alert means and what the first response should be. This is distinct from the runbooks (which address known scenarios) — monitoring handoff ensures unknown incidents are detected and routed.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "monitoring_handoff", Phase 6, triggers: "Hand off monitoring for [service]", "Set up on-call rotation", "Document alerting for [project]". Scope: Produces the monitoring ownership document mapping each alert to an owner/team, configures on-call tooling, documents what each alert means and its first-response action, and establishes the escalation chain from automated alert to human response.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 (Maintenance) continuous_learning and dependency_management assume a functioning operational feedback loop. Without a monitoring handoff, that loop has no inputs. Phase 5.75 (Beta) rate_limiting and error_boundaries were implemented — but their alert owners are undefined at handoff.

