## Finding: Runbook Automation Is Not Addressed

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: disaster_recovery provides detailed human-executable runbooks (8 scenarios). However, there is no skill addressing the automation of these runbooks: converting manual runbook steps into executable scripts, building self-healing automation, or using tools like AWS Systems Manager Runbooks, PagerDuty Process Automation, or simple shell scripts to automate recovery steps. The skill acknowledges "During an incident is the worst time to figure out your recovery process" — but stops short of automating the process for faster and more reliable execution.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "runbook_automation", Phase 6, triggers: "Automate runbook for [scenario]", "Convert runbook to script", "Self-healing automation for [service]". Scope: Transforms the human-executable runbooks from disaster_recovery into automated executable scripts or workflows, covering script templates for the 8 standard scenarios, integration with monitoring tooling to trigger automation on alert, and testing protocols for automated runbooks.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 (Maintenance) dependency_management and sop_standards assume runbooks exist — runbook automation makes them more reliable. Phase 5.75 (Beta) rate_limiting could benefit from auto-remediation scripts.

