## Finding: No Mechanism to Verify the Product Is Actually Deployable by Someone Other Than Its Builder

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Reasoning backward from a perfect handoff: if Phase 6 was completed ideally, a new engineer who had never touched the codebase would be able to clone the repo, follow the setup documentation, and run the application successfully within 2 hours. Currently: api_reference documents endpoints (assuming the app is already running), user_documentation helps users (assuming the app is deployed), disaster_recovery handles failures (assuming the app was successfully deployed). None of these skills include a "Stranger Test" — having someone unfamiliar with the project execute the setup documentation from scratch and validating that it works end-to-end. If the handoff documentation cannot guide a stranger to a running system, it has failed its core purpose.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to "knowledge_audit" skill (Loop 1): a mandatory "Stranger Test" protocol — a structured exercise where someone not on the build team executes all setup and deployment documentation from scratch, recording every point of failure or ambiguity, producing a gap list that must be resolved before handoff is declared complete.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Every phase downstream of 6 depends on new team members being able to onboard. If the setup docs fail the Stranger Test, Phase 7 maintenance will immediately incur technical debt from ad-hoc knowledge transfer.

---

## Finding: Credential and Access Management Handoff Is Entirely Absent

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Reasoning backward: a complete handoff must include transferring access. The build team holds: production API keys, database credentials, hosting provider accounts, third-party service accounts (Stripe, SendGrid, etc.), domain registrar access, DNS management credentials, CI/CD pipeline secrets, and monitoring tool logins. Phase 6 has no skill that: (1) inventories all credentials and access points, (2) transfers ownership of accounts from build team to operations team, (3) rotates credentials at handoff (ensuring the outgoing team loses access), (4) documents which roles/people need which access for Phase 7 operations. disaster_recovery references credentials (JWT secret, Stripe webhook secret, DB passwords) but assumes they exist and are known — not that they are inventoried and transferred.
### Proposed Resolution: Skill name "access_handoff", Phase 6, triggers: "Transfer system access", "Credential inventory for handoff", "Access management handoff". Scope: Produces the complete credential inventory (what exists, where it is stored, who currently has access), executes the access transfer workflow (new owners receive access, old owners are removed), rotates all secrets at handoff as a security hygiene step, and documents the ongoing access management policy for Phase 7.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) established secrets management practices. Phase 6 access_handoff closes the loop by transferring those secrets to the new operations team. Without this, the outgoing team retains access to production systems indefinitely — a security violation in any compliance regime.

