## Finding: The Phase Has No Defined Sequence — Skills Are Unordered

### Gap Type: MISSING_HANDOFF
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Reasoning backward: a perfect handoff follows a specific sequence. You cannot write the user documentation before the features are stable. You cannot transfer monitoring ownership before the monitoring exists. You cannot execute the knowledge audit after the build team has dispersed. Phase 6 skills have no defined execution order. The framework provides trigger commands but no orchestrating sequence: which skill runs first? What does each skill depend on from other skills in the same phase? feature_walkthrough (for individual features) should precede doc_reorganize (which reorganizes accumulated walkthroughs). disaster_recovery should be written before monitoring_handoff (which references the runbooks). Without sequencing, teams execute skills in arbitrary order, creating dependencies gaps.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a Phase 6 Orchestration Document (or add an ordering section to the proposed "operational_readiness_review" skill) that defines the mandatory execution sequence: (1) knowledge_audit, (2) feature_walkthrough per feature, (3) user_documentation, (4) api_reference, (5) disaster_recovery, (6) support_enablement, (7) monitoring_handoff, (8) sla_handoff, (9) access_handoff, (10) doc_reorganize, (11) operational_readiness_review.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Lack of sequencing affects every phase but is most critical at Phase 6 because handoff artifacts depend on each other (walkthroughs inform user docs; disaster recovery informs monitoring handoff). Out-of-order execution creates rework.

