## Finding: api_reference Fails for GraphQL-First Projects

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: If the project uses GraphQL (Apollo, Pothos, type-graphql) instead of REST, api_reference provides zero usable guidance. GraphQL documentation requires different tooling: GraphiQL or Apollo Studio for interactive exploration, graphql-inspector for schema change detection, SDL generation from code-first schemas, and subscription documentation patterns. The NestJS-specific content (SwaggerModule, @ApiTags, @ApiOperation) is entirely inapplicable to GraphQL endpoints. In GraphQL-first architectures (increasingly common for complex data requirements), the Phase 6 api_reference skill produces nothing of value. This is a critical stack-context failure mode that affects 20-30% of modern API projects.
### Proposed Resolution: Add GraphQL documentation section to api_reference: schema SDL generation, GraphiQL/Apollo Studio setup, subscription documentation, schema change detection CI (graphql-inspector), and schema-first vs code-first documentation strategies.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Any phase that documents APIs (Phase 3 Build, Phase 4 Secure) will have created GraphQL APIs that go undocumented at Phase 6 handoff if this gap is not addressed.

---

## Finding: community_management Fails for Regulated Industries (HIPAA, PCI, FedRAMP)

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: community_management's governance models (BDFL, Steering Committee, Foundation, Corporate-backed) and funding models (GitHub Sponsors, Open Collective, dual licensing) assume a commercially and legally unconstrained environment. For projects in healthcare (HIPAA), payments (PCI-DSS), government (FedRAMP), or financial services (SOX, FINRA), community management has additional constraints: contributors may need background checks, code contributions must pass security reviews before merge, intellectual property ownership must be formally documented, export control laws (ITAR, EAR) may restrict who can contribute, and government contracts may prohibit certain open source licenses. The skill has zero guidance for regulated-industry community management.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Regulated Industry Considerations" section to community_management: contributor vetting requirements, IP assignment agreements (CLA vs DCO), export control license compatibility matrix, and government contract open source policy guidance.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) addresses compliance requirements during build. If community management at handoff violates those same compliance requirements, Phase 4's work is undermined.

