## Finding: DORA Metrics — No Skill Establishes Baselines at Handoff

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: DORA (DevOps Research and Assessment) defines four key metrics for software delivery performance: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Mean Time to Restore (MTTR). Industry standard (Google SRE, DORA State of DevOps Report) mandates that these baselines be established before a system transitions to maintenance operations, so that Phase 7 can measure whether performance is improving or degrading. Phase 6 has no skill that: measures the current deployment frequency achieved during beta, establishes MTTR baselines from beta incidents, records lead time from commit to production, or documents the change failure rate. Without DORA baselines at handoff, Phase 7 has no performance benchmark — it cannot determine if its changes are improving or worsening the system.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to "operational_readiness_review" skill: a DORA Metrics Baseline section that captures the four DORA metrics from Phase 5-5.75 data, classifies the team as Elite/High/Medium/Low performer per DORA benchmarks, and sets target metrics for Phase 7.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 continuous_learning and documentation_standards are improvement-oriented — but improvement requires a baseline. DORA baselines from Phase 6 are the prerequisite for meaningful Phase 7 performance measurement.

---

## Finding: SRE Error Budget — No Framework Established at Handoff

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Site Reliability Engineering (SRE) practice (Google SRE Book, USENIX SREcon standards) requires that SLOs be established at handoff with associated error budgets — the amount of downtime/errors permissible within the SLO window. Phase 6 has no skill establishing: error budget calculation (e.g., 99.9% uptime = 8.7 hours of downtime/year budget), error budget burn rate monitoring, the freeze policy (what happens when error budget is exhausted — feature freeze, incident-only work), and the error budget review cadence. disaster_recovery defines SEV levels but not the error budget framework that governs how aggressively Phase 7 can make changes. Without an error budget, Phase 7 makes changes without understanding the reliability risk they are incurring.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to the proposed "sla_handoff" skill (Loop 1): an Error Budget section defining SLO percentage, error budget calculation, burn rate alert thresholds, and the change freeze policy triggered by budget exhaustion.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 maintenance change velocity should be governed by the error budget. Without it, maintenance changes happen at arbitrary cadence with no reliability guardrails.

---

## Finding: ISO 27001 / SOC 2 — No Asset Register Transfer at Handoff

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: ISO 27001 (Annex A.8 - Asset Management) and SOC 2 (CC6.1 - Logical Access Security) require that information assets be formally catalogued with assigned owners, and that ownership transfer be documented when stewardship changes. Phase 6 handoff is precisely such a stewardship change. No Phase 6 skill produces: an Information Asset Register (IAR) cataloguing all data assets (databases, file stores, backup archives, API keys, customer data), their classification (public/internal/confidential/restricted), their current owner, and the new owner after handoff. For any organization pursuing or maintaining ISO 27001 or SOC 2 certification, undocumented asset transfer at Phase 6 is an audit finding.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to the proposed "access_handoff" skill (Loop 4): an Information Asset Register section following ISO 27001 Annex A.8 format, capturing all assets, their classification, processing activities, and ownership transfer records.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) establishes security controls. Phase 6 must transfer those controls with their assets. Phase 7 inherits the responsibility for maintaining ISO 27001/SOC 2 compliance — but cannot do so without knowing what assets it owns.

---

## Finding: OWASP Secure Handoff — No Penetration Test Sign-Off Required

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: OWASP's Software Assurance Maturity Model (SAMM) and NIST SP 800-64 both recommend that a formal security assessment (penetration test or security review sign-off) be completed before a system is handed off from development to production operations. Phase 4 (Secure) addresses security controls during build. But Phase 6 has no skill requiring: a final penetration test or security review before GA, a vulnerability assessment report as a handoff artifact, a CVE/vulnerability registry establishing the security baseline at handoff, or a formal security acceptance sign-off. If Phase 4 was completed months before Phase 6, new vulnerabilities may have been introduced during the Phase 5-5.75 development that was done after the security phase.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to "operational_readiness_review" skill: a Security Sign-Off Gate requiring a current (< 90 days) security assessment report (penetration test summary, vulnerability scan results), all critical/high findings resolved or risk-accepted with documented justification, and a CISO/security lead sign-off.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) is the primary security phase, but Phase 6 is the last opportunity before production operations begin. Without a security sign-off at handoff, Phase 7 may inherit a system with unresolved vulnerabilities.

---

## Finding: NIST CSF — No Cybersecurity Framework Mapping at Handoff

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) 2.0 defines six functions: Govern, Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover. The "Recover" function is explicitly about restoration of services post-incident and handoff of recovery responsibilities. Phase 6's disaster_recovery addresses Respond and Recover at the technical level but does not produce the NIST CSF mapping artifact that regulated enterprises require: which CSF subcategories does this system satisfy, who is the system owner (CSF Govern), what are the information flows (CSF Identify), and how does the recovery plan map to NIST SP 800-184 (Guide for Cybersecurity Event Recovery)?
### Proposed Resolution: Add to "disaster_recovery" skill: a NIST CSF mapping appendix that maps each runbook to the CSF Respond/Recover subcategories, and a System Owner declaration satisfying CSF Govern requirements.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Organizations requiring NIST CSF compliance cannot use disaster_recovery as a compliance artifact without this mapping. Phase 7 maintenance operations inherit CSF compliance responsibility.

---

## Finding: CIS Controls — No Baseline Configuration Documentation at Handoff

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: CIS Controls v8 (Safeguard 4.1 - Establish and Maintain a Secure Configuration Process) requires that a secure configuration baseline be documented and transferred with system ownership. Phase 6 has no skill producing: a hardened configuration baseline document (what security configurations were applied to servers, containers, databases, and network components), a CIS Benchmark compliance summary, or a configuration drift detection setup (ensuring Phase 7 maintenance changes don't erode the security baseline). Phase 4 (Secure) may have applied CIS hardening — but if it is not documented and transferred at Phase 6, the configuration baseline is unknown to Phase 7 operators.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to "knowledge_audit" skill (Loop 1): a "Secure Configuration Baseline" section capturing all hardened configurations, CIS Benchmark version applied, deviations from benchmark with justifications, and the configuration drift detection mechanism in place.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 7 dependency_management changes (OS upgrades, package updates) may inadvertently reset security configurations without a documented baseline to compare against.

